text: The two leads are cast against type. Pierce Brosnan is most famous for portraying James Bond, here he's an Ex-IRA man in some sort of power-sharing deal with the British Government, and Jackie Chan is a vengeful Father who resorts to terrorism himself to discover then names of the bombers who killed his family. Pierce could be replaying his role from the Long Good Friday, but Jackie Chan character is a much more ambiguous figure. How long before the hero becomes the Villain? The Dark Knight gave a grim answer to that, but this is certainly intriguing. Has Jackie Chan ever played a villain in any of his Movies before?

text: its amazing, reading all the comments, no one referenced the serious plot holes.   this movie is like enjoying a fight where the underdog kid in school beats up a jock. but the wrong jock, not the bully jock, an innocent jock. and everyone keeps cheering him on to keep kicking his ass, but its still the wrong ass he is kicking.   brosnan's character didnt know who. and did whatever he could to find out who did it. jackie just wont accept the truth and hinders brosnan from finding out who the real criminal is.  even when he does find out who, and tells jackie, jackie still blames brosnan and frames him in the end.   brosnan got used by his friend, his wife, his mistress, who all got found out, exposed to the brits, killed for it and brosnan still gets framed by jackie in the end. [did anyone else notice? that the wife and mistress were both using brosnan for the bad boss but are never referenced together? as if the plot would fall apart if mentioned, aside from the plot hole mentioned above] why didnt brosnan and or the brit cop, invite jackie to see all what they are doing to find the bad guys? so in the end, jackie is just as bad but he heralded as a hero by the audience.  nobody else gets this? maybe brosnon should have invited jackie in on the hunt and let the old man surprise them with his skills.  good acting, good directing, nice dialogue, stupid plot holes. if jackie's character was deleted from the movie, it would have not made any difference. no one would have noticed.  finding the bombers was all the movie needed.  jackie only brings the movie down and there wouldnt have been a plot hole.

text: I've already watched it. It's not as good as I thought it would be but it was okay. The movie needs a better soundtrack, and Jackie's role was too one dimensional. I'm afraid, the film makers were trying too hard to make another "Taken" movie. If I was the screen writer, I would add more flashback  scenes about the relationship between the father and his daughter. You have to explain why the father went so far as he did in this movie. Sure, he loved his daughter because she is his daughter. But what exactly makes her so special that he risks his freedom to avenge his daughter? In the real world, you would go to prison when you hunt down criminals by yourself. So why did he do that. I would have love to see more than just another "Liam Neeson" character played by a Chinese actor. This film should have been carried out more carefully. After all, the IRA terrorism is a very complex history. Most people like me (who are not Irish) will find it difficult to understand what the IRA was all about.
